<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Learn DSA</title>
    <link rel='stylesheet' href='/stylesheets/style.css' />
    <%- include('../../partials/head') %>
  </head>
  <body>

    <div class="d-flex">
      <%- include('../../partials/sidebar') %>

      <main class="flex-fill p-4">
        <div class="text-center">
          <h3>Introduction to Trees</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # What is a Tree?

            A **tree** is a hierarchical data structure made up of nodes.

            - One node is designated as the **root**
            - Each node may have **children**
            - Nodes are connected by **edges**

            ####n - 1 edges for n nodes####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Root] --> B[Child 1];
              A --> C[Child 2];
              B --> D[Grandchild];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Key Terminology

            Understanding trees requires knowing key terms:

            - **Root**: Top node of the tree
            - **Leaf**: Node with no children
            - **Parent / Child**: Relationship between nodes
            - **Subtree**: A tree within a tree

            ####height = longest path from root to leaf####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Root] --> B;
              A --> C;
              B --> D[Leaf];
              C --> E[Leaf];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Properties of Trees

            Trees have important structural properties:

            - No cycles (acyclic)
            - Exactly one path between any two nodes
            - Connected structure

            ####edges = nodes - 1####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A --> B;
              A --> C;
              B --> D;
              C --> E;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Types of Trees

            There are many types of trees:

            - **Binary Tree**: Max 2 children per node
            - **Binary Search Tree (BST)**: Ordered structure
            - **Balanced Trees**: Height is minimized
            - **Heap**: Special tree for priority queues

            ####left < root < right####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[10] --> B[5];
              A --> C[15];
              B --> D[2];
              B --> E[7];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div> 

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Why Use Trees?

            Trees are useful for:

            - Representing hierarchical data (e.g., file systems)
            - Fast searching and sorting
            - Efficient insertion and deletion

            ####O(log n) average operations####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Root] --> B[Folder];
              B --> C[File1];
              B --> D[File2];
              A --> E[Folder2];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div> 
        </div>
        <!-- CONTROLS --> 
        <div class="nav-controls"> 
          <button class="btn btn-outline-dark me-2" id="prev">← Prev</button> 
          <button class="btn btn-outline-dark" id="next">Next →</button> 
        </div> 
        <div class="progress-container"> 
          <div class="progress-bar" id="progress"></div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide-counter"> 
          <span id="current">1</span>/<span id="total">1</span> 
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  </body>
  <script src="/javascripts/render-slides.js"></script>
</html>
